  "prompt": "What is the difference between a beta particle and an electron?",
  "response": "A beta particle and an electron are related but not exactly the same. Here's the distinction:\n\n1. **Beta Particle**: This term refers to a specific type of subatomic particle that is emitted during a certain kind of radioactive decay known as beta decay. There are two types of beta particles:\n   - **Beta-minus (\u03b2-) particles**, which are essentially electrons, emitted from a nucleus when a neutron is converted into a proton, resulting in the release of an electron and an antineutrino.\n   - **Beta-plus (\u03b2+) particles**, which are positrons (the antiparticle of electrons), emitted when a proton is converted into a neutron, releasing a positron and a neutrino.\n\n2. **Electron**: An electron is a fundamental subatomic particle that carries a negative elementary charge. It is one of the building blocks of atoms and exists independently, as well as in various interactions and structures, such as in atomic orbitals or as part of charged particles in conducting materials.\n\nIn summary, while beta-minus particles are a specific type of electron emitted during nuclear decay, electrons themselves are more general particles that play a significant role in atomic structure and various physical processes.",
